Other Tools
***********

The AmigaNCP package contains a few more programs which are meant for
the advanced user.  Since they are also good examples for how to access
the @{b}amigancp.library@{ub}, the source code for most of these utilities can
be found in the @{b}Developer/Source/@{ub} drawer.


 @{" AmigaNCP-Monitor " Link "AmigaNCP-Monitor"}     Monitor network activity
 @{" S3PrintServer " Link "S3PrintServer"}        Print on the Amiga printer
 @{" S3Run " Link "S3Run"}                Run a program on the remote machine


@EndNode

@Node "AmigaNCP-Monitor" "AmigaNCP.guide/AmigaNCP-Monitor"
@Next "S3PrintServer"
@Toc "Other Tools"

AmigaNCP-Monitor
================

The @{i}AmigaNCP-Monitor@{ui} is a utility for monitoring the current network
activity.  It displays an overview over the eight avaible NCP channels,
their users, current connection states and the amount of data that has
been transferred.

@{i}AmigaNCP-Monitor@{ui} may be started either from the shell or from
Workbench.  There are no additional parameters.  The window position
will be saved as a tooltype entry.

The Monitor opens a single window on the workbench screen.  The top
part displays the states of the eight network channels, the bottom part
shows overall statistics and whether NCP is currently connected.

@{b}ThisProc@{ub}
     The network name of the Amiga process using the channel.  The
     first channel is always allocated by the @{b}LINK@{ub} application.

@{b}RemotePr@{ub}
     The name of the remote process.  This may be empty, meaning the
     channel is currently not connected.

     @{b}UnknClnt@{ub} identifies a passive channel connected to an unknown
     client.

     For the first channel, this may be either @{b}ARemLink@{ub}, denoting that
     the current connection has been initiated by the remote link, or
     @{b}PRemLink@{ub}, if the current connection was opened on behalf of the
     @{b}amigancp.library@{ub}.

@{b}Status@{ub}
     This flag array denotes various internal states of
     @{b}amigancp.library@{ub}.

@{b}Bytes Sent@{ub}
     How many bytes have been sent through this channel?

@{b}Bytes Received@{ub}
     How many bytes have been received through this channel?

@{b}Online since@{ub}
     The time on which @{b}amigancp.library@{ub} was started first.  The startup
     time is used by the NCP protocol to determine whether a broken
     connection can be reestablished or not.

@{b}Remote NCP@{ub}
     The remote NCP's startup time.

@{b}Version@{ub}
     The remote NCP's version.  This is generally @{b}2@{ub} for AmigaNCP and
     the Psion S3 and @{b}3@{ub} for the S3a.

@{b}Connected@{ub}
     This will be displayed whenever there is an active connection to
     any remote NCP.


@EndNode

@Node "S3PrintServer" "AmigaNCP.guide/S3PrintServer"
@Next "S3Run"
@Prev "AmigaNCP-Monitor"
@Toc "Other Tools"

S3PrintServer
=============

The @{i}S3PrintServer@{ui} is a small utility which allows you to print from
your Psion directly to a printer connected to the Amiga.  It uses the
Psion's capability to print to a serial printer, and simply passes any
data from the serial port directly to the printer device via raw writes.

You have to turn off the @{b}Remote Link@{ub} on the Psion side and terminate
any NCP application running on the Amiga side before starting the
S3PrintServer.  @{i}If you forget to turn off the Remote Link, junk will be
printed due to misinterpreted NCP packets!@{ui}

You must also set your Psion's printer configuration to serial
printing, with the same baud rate used for NCP connections, turn off
@{b}Xon/Xoff@{ub} and turn on @{b}RTS/CTS@{ub} and @{b}DSR/DTR@{ub} handshaking.  The S3PrintServer
itself reads the serial configuration from the file @{b}ENV:NCP.config@{ub}.

The S3PrintServer uses the raw write capabilities of the @{b}printer.device@{ub}
and therefore ignores any printer driver settings.  However, it respects
your choice on which device to print, and even allows printing via
network printer services, e.g.  @{b}Envoy Network Printing@{ub}.

Therefore, you @{i}must@{ui} select the correct @{b}WDR@{ub} printer driver on the
Psion.  This can be done in the @{b}Printer Setup@{ub} dialog of the @{b}Word@{ub}
application.

Having done all this, you can print from your Psion applications simply
by selecting the @{b}Print...@{ub} menu, just as if the printer was connected
directly to the Psion.


@EndNode

@Node "S3Run" "AmigaNCP.guide/S3Run"
@Prev "S3PrintServer"
@Toc "Other Tools"

S3Run
=====

The @{i}S3Run@{ui} utility uses the @{b}LINK@{ub} application's capability to launch a
process on the remote side.  It's a shell only program which takes one
or two parameters: @{b}S3Run filename commandline@{ub}

The first argument denotes the file name of the remote program to run,
for example @{b}TEST.IMG@{ub}.  Due to NCP restrictions, this may only be a
program on the Psion's top level directory or ROM.

The second argument may contain the command line to be passed to the
created process.  This argument may be omitted, in which case no command
line will be passed.

You may use @{b}\\xx@{ub} escaping to insert the hexadecimal code @{b}xx@{ub} into the
command line.  See `the Psion SIBO SDK Manual' for more information on
S3 command lines.


@EndNode

@Node "API" "AmigaNCP.guide/API"
@Next "Index"
@Prev "Other Tools"
@Toc "Main"

API
***

This part of the AmigaNCP documentation describes the use of AmigaNCP
services within custom applications.  It assumes a broad knowledge of
programming AmigaOS.


 @{" NCP Implementation " Link "NCP Implementation"} 	   Using NCP in general
 @{" Function Reference " Link "Function Reference"}      Functions in @{b}amigancp.library@{ub}
 @{" Errors " Link "Errors"}                  Error codes from library calls


@EndNode

@Node "NCP Implementation" "AmigaNCP.guide/NCP Implementation"
@Next "Function Reference"
@Toc "API"

NCP Implementation
==================

The Psion NCP network protocol consists of four layers:

@{b}Serial Layer@{ub}
     A simple asynchronous serial 8/N/1 connection.  This is in fact
     the hardware serial connection built into the 3-Link.

@{b}Packet Layer@{ub}
     A packet protocol providing checksums and multiple
     retransmissions.  It is called @{b}LLMAC@{ub} and somewhat based on the
     MNP type protocols.

@{b}NCP Layer@{ub}
     NCP provides up to eight independant data streams between local
     and remote processes.  Under the Psion OS, a process may use only
     one NCP channel at a time.

@{b}Application Layer@{ub}
     Applications built on top of the NCP data stream service.  This
     includes the remote file system and remote file server.  There is
     also a supervisory application called @{i}LINK@{ui} which controls the
     server setup.

A more detailed description of NCP usage from the Psion side can be
found in the `Psion SIBO SDK Manual, I/O Devices Reference'.

On the Amiga side, the serial layer is provided through any standard
EXEC serial device, normally this will be the internal port's
@{b}serial.device@{ub}.  The packet and NCP layers have been built into the
@{b}amigancp.library@{ub}.

Besides these basic layers, also the supervisory @{i}LINK@{ui} application
resides in the
@{b}amigancp.library@{ub}.

All network services are accessible via function calls to the
@{b}amigancp.library@{ub}.  In order to use these functions, you have to open the
@{b}amigancp.library@{ub} first:

         #include <libraries/ncp.h>
     
         struct Library *NCPBase;
         NCPBase = OpenLibrary( "amigancp.library", NCP_VERSION );
         if( !NCPBase )
             fail_app();

If you use SAS/C 6.50 or above, you may want to use the link library
@{b}ncp.lib@{ub} provided in the development toolkit.  It contains a
constructor/destructor pair that automatically opens/closes the
@{b}amigancp.library@{ub} upon startup/termination of your application.

If you are not using C, you'll have to build your own language specific
glue definitions.  A function description file
(@{b}Developer/FD/ncp_lib.fd@{ub}) has been included.  The AmigaNCP
programming interface doesn't use any fancy data structures, so you
should have no problems with other programming languages.

The NCP network services are based on @{i}channels@{ui}.  A channel is a
connection between a local and a remote processes.  In the Psion EPOC
environment, a channel is bound to a single process and bears the name
of that process.  AmigaNCP allows you to specify arbitrary names for
your channels, along with having multiple channels within a single
application, if you wish to do so.

A channel may be opened in either @{i}active@{ui} or @{i}passive@{ui} mode.  An active
channel attempts to connect to a remote process with a given name and
refuses to open if the remote process doesn't exists or already is busy
with some other connection.  A passive channel just sits around
awaiting a connection from the remote site.  Passive channels are
normally used for server applications awaiting connections from their
clients, whereas active channels are used by clients to contact their
server application.

I/O via NCP is done either @{i}synchronously@{ui} or @{i}asynchronously@{ui}.  The I/O
interface of the @{b}amigancp.library@{ub} is quite similar to the EXEC device
I/O interface.  See the function descriptions of the NCP I/O functions
for more details.

The @{b}Developer/Source/@{ub} drawer provides some examples to show the use of
the
@{b}amigancp.library@{ub} calls.


@EndNode

